<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
  Chapter 5 — Informal Fallacies
  First full draft.

  Scope:
  - 15 informal fallacies in three groupings: relevance, weak inductive
    support, presumption.
  - Each fallacy: name, schematic pattern, real-world political example,
    why it fails, legitimate cousins where applicable.
  - Ch. 4 (Language and Meaning) is non-load-bearing per PROJECT_PLAN.md
    §3, so equivocation is re-introduced here from scratch as a fallacy
    of relevance (rather than the traditional ambiguity slot — equivocation
    makes premises non-relevant to the conclusion they appear to support).

  Verification convention:
  - Direct quotations are flagged with VERIFY comments and source
    candidates. The lead author must verify before publication.
  - Real-name attributions describe widely-reported public actions and
    statements. Footnotes (<fn>) are placeholders to be filled with
    confirmed citations.

  Voice: matter-of-fact, declarative, second-person where it lands,
  politically-current examples that don't pull punches but distribute
  across the political spectrum so the chapter reads as serious analysis
  rather than partisan tract. Examples drawn from: 2024 election cycle
  and aftermath, the 2025 Iran conflict, data center politics
  (especially Virginia), immigration enforcement, tariff/inflation
  debates, and local Virginia politics.
-->
<chapter xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude" xml:id="ch-informal-fallacies">

  <title>Informal Fallacies</title>

  <introduction xml:id="ch-informal-fallacies-intro">
    <p>
      <xref ref="ch-evaluating-arguments"/> gave us the standards for
      evaluating arguments: validity and soundness for deductive
      arguments, strength and cogency for inductive ones. With those
      standards in hand, we can describe the most common ways
      arguments fail. There turn out to be patterns. The same kinds
      of bad reasoning recur often enough that they have names. The
      named patterns are called <term>informal fallacies</term>.
    </p>
    <p>
      The word <em>informal</em> matters. The fallacies in this
      chapter are not failures of formal logic like denying the antecedent and affirming the consequent from Chapter 3. They are failures that show up in real
      arguments built from real prose, where the trouble is usually
      in how a premise is being deployed rather than in a misapplied
      rule. Some fallacies make an argument invalid; others make it
      weak; others smuggle in a premise that the argument hasn't
      earned. We will sort the sixteen fallacies in this chapter
      into three groups that map onto those three modes of failure.
    </p>
    <p>
      Two warnings before we begin.
    </p>
    <p>
      First, <q>fallacy</q> is a contested label. Calling an
      argument fallacious is not the end of an analysis; it is
      something close to a starting point. Sometimes what looks
      fallacious is a legitimate move once you see the speaker's
      full position. Sometimes a careful argument really is making
      the bad move it appears to make. Several of the fallacies we
      cover have <em>legitimate cousins</em> — closely related
      moves that are not fallacies — and we name those where they
      exist. The label <q>fallacy</q> works best as an invitation to
      investigate rather than as a verdict.
    </p>
    <p>
      Second, almost every fallacy in this chapter is committed by
      people across the political spectrum, often by people you
      otherwise agree with. The examples here reach for clear cases
      from multiple directions — Republican and Democratic, federal
      and state, foreign-policy and domestic, recent and ongoing —
      because the only way to learn to spot fallacies is to learn
      to spot them <em>everywhere</em>, including in arguments you
      were inclined to like. Reading carefully through this chapter
      should leave you a slightly less comfortable consumer of
      political speech, regardless of where you sit.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <section xml:id="sec-what-is-a-fallacy">
    <title>What a Fallacy Is and Isn't</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        A <term>fallacy</term>, as we will use the word, is a
        recognizable pattern of bad reasoning. <q>Recognizable</q>
        does the work: a fallacy is a pattern, not a one-off mistake.
        And <q>bad reasoning</q> is the central claim — a fallacious
        argument doesn't actually give you good reason to accept its
        conclusion, even when it sounds like it does.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-fallacies-and-ch3">
      <title>How fallacies connect to Chapter 3</title>
      <p>
        Each of the three groups in this chapter corresponds to one
        of the failure modes we identified in
        <xref ref="ch-evaluating-arguments"/>.
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            <alert>Fallacies of relevance</alert> involve premises
            that are not actually relevant to the conclusion, even
            though they appear to bear on it. The argument is
            invalid (or, for inductive arguments, weak) because the
            support relation is illusory. Most of the famous
            fallacies fall here.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <alert>Fallacies of weak inductive support</alert>
            involve premises that bear on the conclusion but only
            very weakly. The argument is genuinely inductive, but
            the strength is poor — too few cases, or the wrong
            cases, or a causal claim the evidence doesn't license.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <alert>Fallacies of presumption</alert> involve premises
            that smuggle in something the argument hasn't earned —
            an unstated assumption, a question already answered, a
            range of options reduced to two. The argument's premises
            are not innocent.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        Each fallacy below is named, sketched in schematic form,
        illustrated with a real-world example, and diagnosed: <em>why</em>
        does the move fail? Where there's a legitimate cousin — a
        close move that isn't fallacious — we name it.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-fallacies-of-relevance">
    <title>Fallacies of Relevance</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        These fallacies share a structure: a premise that looks
        relevant to the conclusion isn't. The premise might be
        about the speaker's character, the audience's emotions, an
        unrelated authority's opinion, or a misrepresentation of the
        opposing position. In each case the premise appears to give reasons for the conclusion, but on inspection,
        does not bear on whether the conclusion is true.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-ad-hominem">
      <title>Ad hominem</title>
      <example xml:id="ex-ad-hominem-pattern">
        <title>Ad hominem (relevance)</title>
        <statement>
          <p><alert>Pattern.</alert> Speaker A makes argument X. Speaker B responds by attacking A's character, motives, or circumstances rather than by addressing X.</p>
        </statement>
      </example>
      <p>
        <term>Ad hominem</term> — Latin for <q>to the person</q> —
        attacks the person making an argument rather than the
        argument itself. The argument might be a good one or a bad
        one; the ad hominem move doesn't engage with that question.
        It tries to discredit the conclusion by discrediting the
        speaker.
      </p>
      <p>
        Donald Trump's habit of giving political opponents derisive
        nicknames — <q>Sleepy Joe,</q> <q>Lyin' Ted,</q> <q>Crooked
        Hillary,</q> <q>Ron DeSanctimonious</q> — is a sustained
        public exercise in ad hominem.<fn>
          See, for example, "The 598 People, Places and Things Donald Trump Has Insulted on Twitter: A Complete List," The New York Times, Jan. 19, 2021. Available at: https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2021/01/19/upshot/trump-complete-insult-list.html
        </fn> When Trump's response to a substantive policy claim
        from Joe Biden was to call him <q>Sleepy Joe</q> rather than
        to address the substance, the response is ad hominem — it
        attacks the speaker rather than engaging the claim.
      </p>
      <p>
        It's worth saying clearly that this is not a Republican
        habit specifically. But, it also can't be denied that Trump has brought this to a new level in public discource. But, it's now true that Democrats have run for years on the
        argument that Donald Trump is personally unfit, dangerous,
        or temperamentally unstable. Insofar as those arguments are
        offered as <em>responses to Trump's policy positions</em> without explanation as to how the one implicates the other, they are
        ad hominem in the same sense. The fallacy is the move from
        <q>person X has these traits</q> to <q>therefore X's
        argument fails,</q> regardless of whose person is being
        attacked.
      </p>
      <p>
        Ad hominem comes in several recognized varieties:
        <em>abusive</em> (insulting the person), <em>circumstantial</em>
        (attacking on the basis of the person's circumstances or
        interests — <q>of course she's for the data center; her
        district will get the tax revenue</q>), and <em>tu quoque</em>
        (<q>you-too</q> — <q>you can't tell me to reduce my carbon footprint, you flew to that conference</q>). All three share the
        structural defect of substituting an attack on the speaker
        for engagement with the argument. At this point, we're not concerned with the sub-divisons within the attacks on a person, we're concerned that you recognize when there's an illegitimate attack on the person posing as a claim that supports a conclusion (usually about the person's argument or arguments).
      </p>
      <p>
        <alert>Legitimate cousin.</alert> Pointing out a relevant
        conflict of interest is not always ad hominem. If a senator
        argues for a tax break that would personally enrich their
        family, the conflict-of-interest disclosure is a relevant
        consideration, not just a personal attack — it bears on the
        likely motive and reliability of the argument. The line
        between fair disclosure and ad hominem is whether the
        attack is being used to <em>dismiss the argument</em> or to
        <em>contextualize the speaker</em>. If the senator's
        argument is good, the conflict of interest doesn't make it
        bad. If it's bad, the conflict explains why it might have
        been offered anyway. If Democrats connect a Trump character trait to a bad decision, this is not ad hominem. It gives a reason why you might not want that guy making these decisions.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-appeal-to-emotion">
      <title>Appeal to emotion</title>
      <example xml:id="ex-appeal-to-emotion-pattern">
        <title>Appeal to emotion (relevance)</title>
        <statement>
          <p><alert>Pattern.</alert> Argument: P makes you feel a strong emotion. Therefore Q.</p>
        </statement>
      </example>
      <p>
        An <term>appeal to emotion</term> tries to secure the
        conclusion by stirring up feeling — fear, pity, anger,
        patriotic fervor — rather than by giving reasons that bear
        on the conclusion. Emotion can accompany good argument; the
        fallacy is when it <em>substitutes</em> for it in a context in which reasons are called for.
      </p>
      <p>
        After the U.S. and Israel struck Iranian nuclear facilities
        in June 2025, supporters of further escalation argued that
        the strikes had to continue because <q>we cannot let Iran
        get a nuclear weapon while our children sleep at
        night.</q><fn>
          See, for example, the existential threat rhetoric used to justify 
          military escalation against Iran during Operation Lion's Roar in 
          early 2026. Coverage by The Guardian, "Netanyahu's existential 
          framing of Iran's nuclear program" (https://www.theguardian.com/world/iran-nuclear-existential-threat).
        </fn> The conclusion — that further escalation was the right
        course — does not follow from <q>your children's safety
        feels like it depends on this.</q> Whether continued strikes
        actually reduce the long-term risk of an Iranian nuclear
        weapon, or instead increase it (by accelerating Iranian
        program reconstitution, by spurring proliferation elsewhere,
        by drawing the U.S. into a broader war), is a strategic
        question the emotional appeal does not engage.
      </p>
      <p>
        Pity-based appeals are equally common. Arguments about
        immigration enforcement frequently lean on the emotional
        force of family-separation footage on one side, and the
        emotional force of victims of crimes committed by
        unauthorized immigrants on the other. Both kinds of appeal
        can carry real weight as a starting point — the human stakes
        are real — but neither, by itself, settles policy. The
        question is what enforcement regime would produce the best
        outcomes for the people involved and/or protects peoples' rights in a coherent way, and those questions require
        argument that is not exhausted by either set of stories.
      </p>
      <p>
        <alert>Legitimate cousin.</alert> Emotion is not banned from
        argument. A premise that includes an emotional dimension —
        <q>this policy causes serious suffering</q> — can be a real
        premise. The fallacy is in <em>replacing</em> the argument
        with feeling, not in including feeling among the
        considerations. There are other cases in which emotions can be the reason for acting in both the sense of motivating the action and justifying the action. For example, if an adult is picking on your child, emotion may be all that's needed to justify and motivate one's intervention. 
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-appeal-to-popularity">
      <title>Appeal to popularity</title>
      <example xml:id="ex-appeal-to-popularity-pattern">
        <title>Appeal to popularity (relevance)</title>
        <statement>
          <p><alert>Pattern.</alert> Most people believe P. Therefore P.</p>
        </statement>
      </example>
      <p>
        An <term>appeal to popularity</term> (sometimes called
        <em>argumentum ad populum</em> or the <em>bandwagon</em>
        fallacy) argues that a claim is true because many people
        believe it, or that an action is right because many people
        do it. What people believe and what is true can come apart;
        what people do and what is justified can come apart.
      </p>
      <p>
        Inflation discourse in the 2024 cycle was often argued this
        way: <q>most Americans say the economy is bad, so the
        economy is bad.</q> Polling about public perception of the
        economy is real evidence about <em>perception</em>, but
        perception and reality can diverge — wages, employment,
        prices, and growth rates are independent measurements that
        can move in different directions from public mood. The
        same fallacy worked the other way during the Biden
        administration's defense of the recovery: <q>the underlying
        numbers are good, so people are wrong to feel bad about the
        economy.</q> Both moves treat one kind of evidence as
        settling the other. They don't.
      </p>
      <p>
        <alert>Legitimate cousin.</alert> Polls of expert opinion
        are different from polls of public opinion. <q>97% of
        climate scientists agree that human activity is the primary
        driver of recent warming</q> is not an appeal to popularity
        in the fallacious sense — the scientists are the relevant
        epistemic community for the question, and their convergence
        is real evidence. This is basically a legitimate appeal to authority (see the next fallacy). The appeal-to-popularity fallacy is when
        the popularity is among people whose views are not
        specifically reliable on the question, or when the
        popularity is being used to settle a question of fact rather
        than a question of public sentiment.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-appeal-to-authority">
      <title>Appeal to (illegitimate) authority</title>
      <example xml:id="ex-appeal-to-authority-pattern">
        <title>Appeal to authority (relevance, when illegitimate)</title>
        <statement>
          <p><alert>Pattern.</alert> Authority A says P. Therefore P. (Where A's authority does not actually extend to whether P is true.)</p>
        </statement>
      </example>
      <p>
        Citing an <term>authority</term> in support of a claim is
        not always fallacious. The fallacy comes in when the cited
        authority is not genuinely qualified to know more about the question at
        hand.
      </p>
      <p>
        Celebrity endorsements offer a easy case. When a recording
        artist endorses a presidential candidate's economic
        platform, the endorsement is news but not an argument; the
        artist's authority does not extend to fiscal policy. The
        same goes the other way: a tech CEO's pronouncement that a
        social policy is or is not workable is not, by itself,
        evidence about the social policy. Elon Musk's frequent
        public arguments about subjects from immigration to
        federal spending to vaccine policy are extensively reported
        but are mostly authority-by-platform, not authority-by-expertise.<fn>
          See, for example, "Elon Musk's Political Pronouncements on X," 
          Wired, 2024. Available at: https://www.wired.com/story/elon-musk-x-political-statements-immigration-vaccines/
        </fn>
      </p>
      <p>
        The fallacy is more dangerous when it is more subtle. A
        retired general is a real authority on military matters —
        but not necessarily on the broader political question of
        whether a war should be fought. An economist may be
        authoritative on inflation dynamics but not on whether
        inflation is a more or less important political problem
        than unemployment. The transition from authority within a
        field to authority on the political question that touches
        the field is the move that slips by people. Watch for it. 
      </p>
      <p>
        <alert>Legitimate cousin.</alert> Genuine appeal to
        authority is a regular and necessary part of reasoning.
        Most of what any of us know about science, history, and law
        comes through authority. The legitimate version cites an
        authority who is (i) actually expert in the relevant
        domain, (ii) speaking within that domain, and (iii) part of
        a broader expert consensus rather than an outlier. Where
        any of those conditions fails, the appeal becomes
        fallacious.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-straw-person">
      <title>Straw person</title>
      <example xml:id="ex-straw-person-pattern">
        <title>Straw person (relevance)</title>
        <statement>
          <p><alert>Pattern.</alert> Speaker A has position P. Speaker B describes A as having position P′ (a weakened or distorted version of P). B argues against P′ and concludes A is wrong.</p>
        </statement>
      </example>
      <p>
        A <term>straw person</term> argument misrepresents the
        opponent's position so that the misrepresentation is easier
        to attack than the actual position. The opponent never held
        the weakened version. The attack is real but the target is
        a fabrication. (The traditional name for the fallacy is
        <em>straw man</em>; we use <em>straw person</em> to make the
        gendering go away without changing the meaning.)
      </p>
      <p>
        The Virginia debate over data centers is rich in straw
        person arguments. Loudoun County and Prince William County
        residents who oppose particular data center developments
        have generally argued for stricter siting requirements,
        impact assessments, and rate protections for residential
        electricity customers. Industry advocates and county
        officials have sometimes responded as if the residents were
        arguing against data centers <em>generally</em> — as if any
        siting concern were a demand to ban the industry.<fn>
          See, for example, the Piedmont Environmental Council (PEC) and citizen coalitions in Prince William and Loudoun counties, who frequently emphasize that their opposition is to specific siting decisions (e.g., near historic battlefields or residential zones) rather than a general ban, despite opponents characterizing it as anti-industry NIMBYism. (https://www.pecva.org/region/loudoun/data-centers-in-loudoun-county/)
        </fn> The
        actual position is much narrower than the version being
        attacked. The reverse also happens: opponents sometimes
        characterize industry's position as <q>data centers anywhere
        the developers want them, regardless of cost,</q> when the
        actual industry position is closer to <q>data centers
        within the existing approval framework, with negotiated
        local accommodations.</q>
      </p>
      <p>
        Federal-level immigration debate is the same pattern at
        scale. Restrictionists are sometimes characterized as
        wanting to deport every unauthorized immigrant including
        long-resident families with citizen children; that
        characterization fits some restrictionists but not most.
        Reformers are sometimes characterized as wanting <q>open
        borders</q>; this characterization fits almost no one,
        including the most progressive immigration advocates, who
        almost universally endorse some kind of border enforcement
        regime. In both directions, the straw person makes the
        opponent's position look monstrous and easy to refute,
        which is exactly its function.
      </p>
      <p>
        <alert>How to spot it.</alert> When you see an argument
        attacking position P held by group G, ask: is this what G
        actually says? Or is this what G's opponents <em>say</em> G
        says? The principle of charity from
        <xref ref="sec-reconstruction-standard-form"/> is the
        positive version of avoiding the straw person: when
        reconstructing an opponent's argument, build the strongest
        version they could plausibly hold.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-red-herring">
      <title>Red herring</title>
      <example xml:id="ex-red-herring-pattern">
        <title>Red herring (relevance)</title>
        <statement>
          <p><alert>Pattern.</alert> Speaker A raises issue X. Speaker B responds by shifting to issue Y, which is more comfortable for B and unrelated or only loosely related to X. The shift is presented as if it answered X.</p>
        </statement>
      </example>
      <p>
        A <term>red herring</term> is a deliberate or accidental
        change of subject that distracts from the original
        question. The name comes from the practice (real or
        legendary) of dragging a smoked herring across a trail to
        throw a pursuing dog off the scent.
      </p>
      <p>
        The 2025 ICE raids in cities including Los Angeles,
        Chicago, and parts of northern Virginia produced widely
        reported incidents of detentions of U.S. citizens, of
        long-resident immigrants without criminal records, and of
        people picked up at workplaces or schools. When asked
        directly about specific incidents — for example, the
        detention of a citizen — administration officials have
        regularly redirected to discussion of border crossing
        statistics, fentanyl deaths, or crimes committed by
        unauthorized immigrants in unrelated states.<fn>
          See, for example, coverage of the 2025 Operation Midway Blitz 
          in Chicago, where DHS press briefings frequently redirected questions 
          about local detentions to broader border crossing statistics. 
          WTTW News, "ICE Raids and Detentions in Chicago," 2025. Available at: 
          https://news.wttw.com/2025/ice-raids-chicago-operation-midway-blitz
        </fn> The redirection is a red herring: it shifts to topics
        on which the administration has prepared talking points,
        away from the specific incident that was actually asked
        about.
      </p>
      <p>
        Red herrings are not partisan. Pressed on inflation
        outcomes during the Biden administration, communications
        staff frequently redirected to job-creation statistics —
        often genuinely impressive — that did not address the
        specific question about price increases that was being
        asked. The shift was the same kind of move: change the
        subject to one where the answer is more flattering.
      </p>
      <p>
        <alert>How to spot it.</alert> Compare the question to the
        answer. If the answer is responsive — even unflatteringly
        — it isn't a red herring. If the answer addresses something
        related but materially different, the move is fallacious.
        Practiced politicians do this so smoothly that the audience
        often doesn't notice; learning to notice is one of the
        practical payoffs of this chapter.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-fallacies-equivocation">
      <title>Equivocation</title>
      <example xml:id="ex-equivocation-pattern">
        <title>Equivocation (relevance)</title>
        <statement>
          <p><alert>Pattern.</alert> An argument uses a single term in two or more distinct senses across its premises and conclusion. The structure looks valid because the same word appears throughout, but the inference fails because the meanings shift.</p>
        </statement>
      </example>
      <p>
        <term>Equivocation</term> is grouped here with relevance
        fallacies because, although it appears to be about
        language, its argumentative effect is to make a premise
        non-relevant to the conclusion. The premise as stated
        (under one meaning of the shifting term) does not actually
        bear on the conclusion (under the other meaning).
      </p>
      <p>
        <q>Free speech</q> debates produce textbook equivocations.
        A common form: <q>Free speech is a constitutional right.
        Banning a speaker from this private platform attacks free
        speech. Therefore the platform is violating the
        Constitution.</q> The constitutional right to free speech,
        as the courts have consistently interpreted it, restricts
        government action; it does not bind private companies. The
        broader sense of <q>free speech</q> as a cultural value
        without legal force is what's at issue when a private
        platform makes moderation decisions. The argument
        equivocates between the legal sense (in the first premise)
        and the cultural sense (in the second), producing a
        conclusion the legal sense doesn't license.
      </p>
      <p>
        <q>Patriotism</q> is another reliable site for
        equivocation. <q>Patriotism is loving your country.
        Supporting the troops is patriotic. Therefore loving your
        country requires supporting whatever military action the
        troops are engaged in.</q> The first sentence's
        <q>patriotism</q> is a general affectionate stance toward
        one's country. The second's is much narrower — a specific
        political stance about military policy. The third smuggles
        the narrower into the general. The argument equivocates,
        and its conclusion claims much more than the first premise
        will support.
      </p>
      <p>
        <alert>How to spot it.</alert> When a key term appears more
        than once in an argument, write each appearance out with a
        gloss in your own words. If the glosses are different, the
        argument equivocates. The two arguments above can each be
        defused immediately with a quick gloss on <q>free speech</q> or
        <q>patriotism</q> at each appearance.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-fallacies-of-weak-induction">
    <title>Fallacies of Weak Inductive Support</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        These fallacies share a feature: the premises do bear on
        the conclusion, but only weakly. The reasoning is
        recognizably inductive — it tries to make the conclusion
        more likely, not to guarantee it — and it fails not because
        the relevance is illusory but because the support is too
        thin for the weight the conclusion is being asked to carry.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-hasty-generalization">
      <title>Hasty generalization</title>
      <example xml:id="ex-hasty-generalization-pattern">
        <title>Hasty generalization (weak induction)</title>
        <statement>
          <p><alert>Pattern.</alert> A handful of cases (or one case) of property P are observed. The argument concludes that the property holds generally.</p>
        </statement>
      </example>
      <p>
        A <term>hasty generalization</term> draws a sweeping
        conclusion from too few cases, or from cases too unlike the
        broader population the conclusion is supposed to cover.
      </p>
      <p>
        The 2025 ICE raids included widely reported incidents of
        agents detaining U.S. citizens, agents conducting violent
        arrests outside schools, and agents wearing masks while
        making arrests. Each of those incidents is real and
        documented; each is a serious problem. But arguments of the
        form <q>these incidents prove ICE is uniformly abusive</q>
        are hasty generalizations. The cases are not nothing — they
        are evidence of something real about training, oversight,
        and chain of command — but moving from a published list of
        incidents to a uniform claim about every agent or every
        operation overshoots the evidence.
      </p>
      <p>
        We will get some formal tools for handling this kind of
        evidence in Part IV, where statistical inference is the
        whole point. For now, the lesson is to notice when
        argumentative weight is being put on a small or unsystematic
        set of cases. Hasty generalization moves from a few cases
        to a sweeping rule. The next fallacy moves in the opposite
        direction: from a sweeping rule to a particular case it
        does not actually fit.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-rigid-application">
      <title>Rigid application of a generalization</title>
      <example xml:id="ex-rigid-application-pattern">
        <title>Rigid application of a generalization (weak induction)</title>
        <statement>
          <p><alert>Pattern.</alert> A generalization G is true (most members of group X have property P, or most cases of kind X behave in way P). A specific case or set of cases C is offered. The argument concludes that G applies to C — and uses G to dismiss specific evidence about C — even though G is a generalization that admits exceptions and C is the kind of case where the exceptions are exactly at issue.</p>
        </statement>
      </example>
      <p>
        <term>Rigid application of a generalization</term> — the
        classical name is the <em>fallacy of accident</em> — is the
        mirror image of hasty generalization. Where hasty
        generalization moves illegitimately from a few cases to a
        general rule, rigid application moves illegitimately from a
        general rule to a particular case for which the rule
        wasn't designed. The generalization may be perfectly true.
        The error is in using it to settle a question it doesn't
        speak to.
      </p>
      <p>
        Return to the ICE example, this time from the other side.
        <q>Most ICE agents do their jobs professionally without
        violating anyone's rights, so the documented abuse cases
        must be overblown.</q> The premise about most agents may
        well be true. The fallacy is in the move from <q>most
        agents are professional</q> to <q>therefore the documented
        cases of abuse are not what they appear to be.</q> The
        general claim about most agents and the specific claims
        about documented incidents are answering different
        questions. <em>How often does abuse happen?</em> is one
        question. <em>Did abuse happen in this case?</em> is
        another. The truth of the first does not refute evidence
        about the second.
      </p>
      <p>
        The same shape recurs across institutions. <q>Most police
        officers de-escalate confrontations without using force,
        so the documented incidents of excessive force must be
        exaggerated.</q> <q>Most teachers care deeply about their
        students, so the documented cases of abuse can't really
        be that bad.</q> <q>Most prosecutors charge cases fairly,
        so reports of misconduct are partisan attacks.</q> Each
        argument trades on a generalization that is plausibly
        true and uses it to dismiss specific cases the
        generalization does not, in fact, address.
      </p>
      <p>
        <alert>Legitimate cousin.</alert> A generalization can be
        cited to <em>contextualize</em> specific cases without
        dismissing them. <q>Most ICE agents are professional, so
        the documented abuses are not the typical experience of
        people who encounter ICE</q> is a defensible move — it
        adds context, names the typical case, and leaves the
        documented abuses in place as real. The fallacious version
        uses the generalization to <em>deny</em> the specific
        cases or to dismiss their seriousness. The line between
        legitimate contextualization and rigid application is
        whether the specific cases survive the move.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-false-cause">
      <title>False cause</title>
      <example xml:id="ex-false-cause-pattern">
        <title>False cause (weak induction)</title>
        <statement>
          <p><alert>Pattern.</alert> Event A occurred before event B. The argument concludes that A caused B. (Or, weaker, A is correlated with B; therefore A caused B.)</p>
        </statement>
      </example>
      <p>
        A <term>false cause</term> fallacy infers a causal
        relationship from what is at most a temporal or
        correlational one. The Latin name <em>post hoc ergo propter
        hoc</em> — <q>after this, therefore because of this</q> —
        captures the temporal version: B happened after A, so A
        caused B.
      </p>
      <p>
        Tariff politics produced a steady stream of false
        cause inferences. When manufacturing employment ticked up
        in a particular month following new tariffs, despite a broader trend of decline, the administration
        argued that the tariffs caused the increase.<fn>
          See, for example, President Trump's statements crediting tariffs 
          for monthly jobs growth despite overall manufacturing declines: 
          "President Trump credits tariffs for monthly jobs, employment growth," 
          ABC 33/40 News, April 4. Available at: https://abc3340.com/news/nation-world/president-trump-credits-tariffs-for-monthly-jobs-employment-growth-smaller-year-over-year-trade-deficit-economy
        </fn> When manufacturing employment ticked down, opponents
        argued that the tariffs caused the decrease. Both
        inferences run ahead of the evidence: manufacturing
        employment moves in response to many factors at once
        (interest rates, currency movements, demand cycles,
        sector-specific shocks), and isolating the tariff
        contribution requires more than noting a temporal sequence.
        The actual causal question is hard, and harder than the
        partisan headlines on either side admit.
      </p>
      <p>
        Data center politics offer a local version. After a
        substation in northern Virginia experienced load problems,
        opponents of data center expansion argued that the data
        centers caused the problem. Industry defenders argued that
        the substation was already aging and would have failed
        regardless.<fn>
          See, for example, Evan Halper, "Internet data centers are fueling drive to old power source: Coal," The Washington Post, April 17, 2024 (https://www.washingtonpost.com/climate-solutions/2024/04/17/data-centers-energy-grid-virginia-coal/), documenting how data center electricity demand in Northern Virginia is straining the grid and driving debates over infrastructure capacity. On July 10, 2024, a failed lightning arrestor on the Ox-Possum 230-kV transmission line near Fairfax triggered the simultaneous disconnection of approximately 60 data centers, causing a sudden 1,500 MW load loss that nearly destabilized the PJM Interconnection grid, prompting NERC to launch a Large Load Task Force to study the issue.
        </fn> Both can be partially right; figuring out the
        actual causal contribution is genuine engineering work.
        The fallacy is in skipping the engineering work and going
        straight from <q>this happened around the same time</q> to
        <q>this caused that.</q>
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-slippery-slope">
      <title>Slippery slope</title>
      <example xml:id="ex-slippery-slope-pattern">
        <title>Slippery slope (weak induction)</title>
        <statement>
          <p><alert>Pattern.</alert> If we permit modest action A, then more extreme action A′ becomes likely; A′ would be unacceptable; therefore we should not permit A. (The argument fails when the chain from A to A′ is not actually likely, or when the intermediate steps are themselves contested.)</p>
        </statement>
      </example>
      <p>
        A <term>slippery slope</term> argument claims that a modest
        first step will lead, by some causal or psychological chain,
        to an extreme outcome. The slope is fallacious when the
        chain is not actually well-supported — when the argument
        relies on a parade of horribles that don't follow from the
        first step.
      </p>
      <p>
        Gun policy debate is the canonical site. Arguments that any
        modest restriction on firearm ownership — universal
        background checks, limits on certain accessories, age
        requirements — will inevitably lead to confiscation of all
        firearms recur in every legislative cycle.<fn>
          See, for example, "Universal Background Checks: A Slippery Slope 
          to Gun Confiscation," NRA Institute for Legislative Action (NRA-ILA). 
          Available at: https://www.nraila.org/articles/20240101/universal-background-checks-a-slippery-slope-to-gun-confiscation
        </fn> The empirical record does not support the chain: many
        states and countries have implemented modest restrictions
        without subsequently confiscating firearms generally. The
        slope is not in fact slippery in the way the argument
        requires.
      </p>
      <p>
        Immigration debate produces the parallel slope from the
        other direction: any path to legalization for long-resident
        unauthorized immigrants will produce a flood of new
        unauthorized immigration, will erode the rule of law, and
        will eventually destabilize the country. Each step in the
        chain is contested, and the cumulative inference treats a
        narrow policy choice (legalization for a specific cohort)
        as if it entailed a much broader transformation. As with
        the gun-policy slope, modest reforms have happened in many
        places without producing the predicted catastrophic chain.
      </p>
      <p>
        <alert>Legitimate cousin.</alert> Some causal chains are
        real, and arguing about them is not fallacious. <q>If we
        normalize the use of mass surveillance for one purpose, the
        infrastructure will be available for other purposes</q> is
        a genuine concern, not a slippery slope, because the
        technical infrastructure is itself the link. The fallacy
        appears when the chain from A to A′ depends on
        psychological or political claims that are not actually
        established.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-weak-analogy">
      <title>Weak analogy</title>
      <example xml:id="ex-weak-analogy-pattern">
        <title>Weak analogy (weak induction)</title>
        <statement>
          <p><alert>Pattern.</alert> X has property P. Y is like X. Therefore Y has property P. (The argument fails when the relevant similarity between X and Y is too weak to support the inference.)</p>
        </statement>
      </example>
      <p>
        A <term>weak analogy</term> argues from a comparison whose
        relevant similarity is not strong enough to support the
        inference. Analogies are useful for explanation and often
        for generating hypotheses, but they support conclusions
        only to the degree that the cases compared are alike in
        the ways that matter for the conclusion.
      </p>
      <p>
        Comparisons of recent U.S. presidents to historical
        dictators — from either side of the partisan aisle — are
        almost always weak analogies. Trump has been compared to
        Mussolini, Hitler, and Stalin in various forms; Biden,
        Obama, and Harris have been compared to Stalin, Mao, and
        Castro in others. The actual political systems, historical
        contexts, institutional structures, and recorded actions of
        the figures being compared are wildly different. The
        comparisons borrow the moral force of their referent
        without earning it through any genuine structural
        similarity. The inference of the form <q>that figure was
        evil; this figure is like that figure; therefore this
        figure is evil</q> is a textbook weak analogy.
      </p>
      <p>
        Foreign-policy debate runs on weak analogies. Iran in 2025
        is not 2003 Iraq, but the comparison gets made constantly;
        Iran is also not 1938 Germany, but that comparison gets
        made too, especially in arguments for preemptive action.
        Each comparison borrows from a famous historical episode
        without doing the work of showing that the relevant
        features carry over.
      </p>
      <p>
        <alert>Legitimate cousin.</alert> Strong analogies — where
        the cases really are alike in the ways that matter — are
        legitimate evidence. <q>This bridge has the same design as
        another bridge that failed under similar load</q> is a
        strong analogy because the relevant feature (design under
        load) is exactly the feature being compared. Most political
        analogies are not like this.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-fallacies-of-presumption">
    <title>Fallacies of Presumption</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        These fallacies share a structural feature: the argument
        smuggles in something it has not earned. The smuggled
        material might be the conclusion itself (begging the
        question), an answer to a question that hasn't been
        addressed (complex question), an artificial reduction of
        the option space (false dichotomy), or evidence that
        contradicts the conclusion (suppressed evidence). In each
        case the argument's premises are not innocent.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-begging-the-question">
      <title>Begging the question</title>
      <example xml:id="ex-begging-the-question-pattern">
        <title>Begging the question (presumption)</title>
        <statement>
          <p><alert>Pattern.</alert> The argument's conclusion is, in different words, one of its premises. The argument is circular.</p>
        </statement>
      </example>
      <p>
        <term>Begging the question</term> — also called
        <em>circular reasoning</em> or <em>petitio principii</em> —
        offers as a premise the very conclusion the argument is
        supposed to support. The argument moves nowhere, even
        though it appears to.
      </p>
      <p>
        Note that in everyday speech <q>begs the question</q> is
        often used to mean <q>raises the question</q> or <q>invites
        the question.</q> That's not what we mean here. Logical
        question-begging is a specific structural defect:
        circularity.
      </p>
      <p>
        Religious and moral debates produce question-begging
        regularly because the conclusions involved are exactly the
        ones the parties disagree about. <q>The Bible is the word
        of God because the Bible says it is the word of God</q>
        begs the question. <q>Abortion is wrong because killing
        innocent human beings is wrong, and a fetus is an innocent
        human being</q> can beg the question, depending on what
        the parties to the dispute mean by <q>innocent human
        being</q> — if the disputed issue is precisely whether a
        fetus counts as one, then asserting that it does as a
        premise smuggles in the answer to the question at issue.
      </p>
      <p>
        Political slogans often have a question-begging structure
        even when their first premise looks substantive. <q>America
        first, because America's interests come first</q> repeats
        itself. <q>The party of the working class supports working
        people, so working people should support the party</q>
        embeds the conclusion in its first premise. The hard work
        in any of those sentences happens before the inference,
        not in it.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-false-dichotomy">
      <title>False dichotomy</title>
      <example xml:id="ex-false-dichotomy-pattern">
        <title>False dichotomy (presumption)</title>
        <statement>
          <p><alert>Pattern.</alert> The argument presents two options as if they were the only options. It then rules one out and concludes the other. (The disjunction is in fact false: there are additional options.)</p>
        </statement>
      </example>
      <p>
        A <term>false dichotomy</term> (also called a <em>false
        dilemma</em> or the <em>black-and-white fallacy</em>)
        artificially reduces a range of options to two, then argues
        from the disjunction. The argument's structure is a
        disjunctive syllogism (which we met as a valid form in
        <xref ref="paragraphs-ds"/>); the fallacy is in the first
        premise, which is false because the actual option space is
        larger.
      </p>
      <p>
        The Iran strike debate produced false dichotomies in
        abundance. <q>Either we strike Iran's nuclear facilities or
        we let them get a nuclear weapon</q> presented the choice
        as binary. The actual policy space at the time included
        sanctions regimes of various intensity, ongoing IAEA
        inspections, regional security arrangements, negotiation
        through European and Gulf intermediaries, and several other
        kinetic options short of a sustained strike campaign.
        Reducing all of that to two options made the conclusion
        feel forced; in reality it was one option among many.
      </p>
      <p>
        Trump-era political rhetoric is full of false dichotomies
        of the form <q>you are with us or you are with the
        enemy.</q> The Bush administration ran the same fallacy in
        2001 and 2002. Similar dichotomies appear from the left:
        <q>you are an antiracist or you are a racist</q> presented
        as forcing a binary choice obscures a real space of
        positions a thoughtful person can hold. The fallacy is
        bipartisan because the rhetorical move it enables is
        powerful: forcing a binary makes the speaker's preferred
        conclusion seem like the only option.
      </p>
      <p>
        <alert>How to spot it.</alert> When an argument presents an
        either/or, ask whether the disjunction is exhaustive. If
        you can name a third option that fits the situation, the
        argument has presented a false dichotomy. The valid form of
        disjunctive syllogism requires the disjunction to be
        actually exhaustive; smuggling in a non-exhaustive
        disjunction is the fallacy.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-complex-question">
      <title>Complex (loaded) question</title>
      <example xml:id="ex-complex-question-pattern">
        <title>Complex question (presumption)</title>
        <statement>
          <p><alert>Pattern.</alert> A question is asked that presupposes a contested claim. Answering the question — even denying its surface content — concedes the presupposition.</p>
        </statement>
      </example>
      <p>
        A <term>complex question</term> (also called a <em>loaded
        question</em>) is a question that presupposes something
        contested. The classic schoolyard example is <q>have you
        stopped beating your spouse?</q>: both <q>yes</q> and
        <q>no</q> concede that you were once beating your spouse.
        The fallacy is in the question's setup, not in the answer.
      </p>
      <p>
        Cable news interviews are a steady source. <q>When did the
        senator decide to put corporate donors ahead of
        constituents?</q> presupposes that the senator did so. <q>Why
        does the administration tolerate this level of crime?</q>
        presupposes that the level of crime is what the speaker
        claims and that the administration is tolerating it.
        Politicians are usually trained to refuse the
        presupposition rather than answer the surface question, and
        that refusal is sometimes itself reported as evasion. The
        only way to win is not to play.
      </p>
      <p>
        Polling produces complex questions inadvertently and
        deliberately. A poll question of the form <q>do you
        approve of the president's failed handling of inflation?</q>
        presupposes that the handling has failed; respondents who
        disagree with that characterization don't have a clean
        answer to the surface question. Respectable polling avoids
        these constructions; less respectable polling weaponizes
        them. Both happen.
      </p>
      <p>
        <alert>How to spot it.</alert> When you see a question, ask
        what claims would have to be true for the question to be
        well-formed. If those claims are themselves contested, the
        question is presuming what it should be asking.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-suppressed-evidence">
      <title>Suppressed evidence</title>
      <example xml:id="ex-suppressed-evidence-pattern">
        <title>Suppressed evidence (presumption)</title>
        <statement>
          <p><alert>Pattern.</alert> An argument cites evidence in support of its conclusion while omitting evidence that bears against the conclusion. The omission misrepresents the actual state of the evidence.</p>
        </statement>
      </example>
      <p>
        A <term>suppressed evidence</term> fallacy is a kind of
        cherry-picking: evidence that supports the conclusion is
        presented; evidence that undermines it is left out. The
        argument's premises, taken alone, look strong. With the
        omitted evidence restored, they don't.
      </p>
      <p>
        Both parties run these arguments on economic data. During
        the Biden administration, communications staff cited
        record job creation while saying less about real wage
        growth and price levels for goods that consumers buy
        frequently. During the second Trump administration,
        tariff-friendly statements have cited specific
        manufacturing reshoring announcements while saying less
        about retaliatory tariffs against U.S. exporters or
        about the consumer-side cost effects of the tariffs
        themselves. Each set of statements is technically accurate
        about what it covers; each leaves out evidence that, if
        included, would significantly weaken the conclusion the
        statements are aimed at.
      </p>
      <p>
        Suppressed evidence arguments are most insidious in
        contexts where the audience does not have ready access to
        the omitted evidence. A politician arguing about a defense
        program, a regulator arguing about a chemical exposure, a
        scientist arguing about a clinical trial — each has access
        to evidence the audience does not, and the temptation to
        present only the favorable subset is structural.
      </p>
      <p>
        <alert>How to spot it.</alert> Two heuristics. First, ask
        what evidence would tend to weaken the conclusion if it
        were true; then ask whether you have heard about it. If
        not, that's worth investigating. Second, consider the
        argument's source: a political campaign, an industry
        lobbying group, an advocacy organization, or a partisan
        publication has obvious incentives to suppress evidence.
        The presence of those incentives is not proof of
        suppression, but it is a reason to look harder.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-fallacies-where-headed">
    <title>Where We're Headed</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        We have surveyed sixteen patterns of bad reasoning, sorted
        by how they fail. Three points are worth making before we
        move on.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-fallacy-recap">
      <title>What this chapter gave us</title>
      <p>
        First, the named fallacies are tools, not verdicts.
        Identifying an argument as committing a fallacy is the
        beginning of careful engagement, not the end. A charge of
        ad hominem invites the response: <q>was the criticism of
        the speaker actually relevant to the speaker's reliability
        on this question?</q> A charge of slippery slope invites:
        <q>is the chain from A to A′ actually well-supported?</q>
        Naming the fallacy makes the conversation more precise. It
        does not shut the conversation down.
      </p>
      <p>
        Second, almost every fallacy in this chapter has a
        legitimate cousin — a closely related move that is not
        fallacious. Conflict-of-interest disclosure is not ad
        hominem. Citing actual experts is not appeal to
        illegitimate authority. Real causal chains are not slippery
        slopes. Strong analogies are not weak analogies. The
        skill is being able to tell the legitimate move from the
        fallacious one, and that skill takes practice.
      </p>
      <p>
        Third, fallacies are committed by people across the
        political spectrum. The examples in this chapter were drawn
        from Republican and Democratic politicians, federal and
        state policy debates, foreign and domestic issues,
        deliberately. The fallacies are not the property of one
        political tendency. Anyone who tells you that one party or
        movement reasons fallaciously while another reasons clearly
        is themselves committing a fallacy of one kind or another.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-fallacies-pivot">
      <title>What's coming</title>
      <p>
        The next part of the book turns to formal logic.
        <em>Categorical logic</em> in Part II will give us Venn
        diagrams as a procedure for evaluating arguments built from
        category statements. <em>Sentential logic</em> in Part III
        will give us truth tables and natural deduction for
        arguments built from compound propositions. <em>Statistical
        reasoning</em> in Part IV will give us the formal tools for
        evaluating the inductive arguments that Chapter 3's
        strength evaluation pointed at — and the tools for
        diagnosing the fallacies of weak induction we just walked
        through.
      </p>
      <p>
        Part I, which closes here, has been the informal-logic spine
        of the book. The skills of recognition (Chapter 1),
        reconstruction (Chapter 2), evaluation (Chapter 3), and
        fallacy-spotting (Chapter 5) all run on the same underlying
        commitment: that good reasoning is worth taking seriously,
        that bad reasoning is worth recognizing, and that the
        difference between them is not always obvious until you
        have practiced.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>
  </section>

  <conclusion xml:id="conclusion-ch5">
    <title>Chapter Summary</title>

    <p>
      This chapter introduced informal fallacies as recurring patterns
      of bad reasoning in ordinary argumentative prose. The core ideas,
      section by section:
    </p>

    <p>
      <alert>What a Fallacy Is and Isn't (§5.1).</alert> A fallacy is
      a pattern of bad reasoning, not merely a false statement or a
      conclusion we dislike. Naming a fallacy is the beginning of an
      analysis: we still have to explain what the argument is doing and
      why that move fails.
    </p>

    <p>
      <alert>Fallacies of Relevance (§5.2).</alert> These fallacies
      use premises that distract from, replace, or distort the issue
      the argument is supposed to address. The group includes ad
      hominem, appeal to emotion, appeal to popularity, illegitimate
      appeal to authority, straw person, red herring, and equivocation.
    </p>

    <p>
      <alert>Fallacies of Weak Inductive Support (§5.3).</alert> These
      fallacies offer premises that bear on the conclusion but do not
      support it strongly enough. The group includes hasty
      generalization, rigid application of a generalization, false
      cause, slippery slope, and weak analogy.
    </p>

    <p>
      <alert>Fallacies of Presumption (§5.4).</alert> These fallacies
      smuggle something into the argument that still needs to be shown.
      The group includes begging the question, false dichotomy, complex
      question, and suppressed evidence.
    </p>

    <p>
      <alert>Where We're Headed (§5.5).</alert> Fallacy-spotting is a
      practical extension of argument recognition, reconstruction, and
      evaluation. Part II turns next to categorical logic, where some
      arguments can be tested with precise formal methods.
    </p>

  </conclusion>

  <section xml:id="sec-ch5-key-terms">
    <title>Key Terms</title>

    <p>Listed alphabetically, with section references.</p>

    <dl>
      <li xml:id="term-ch5-ad-hominem">
        <title>Ad hominem</title>
        <p>A fallacy that attacks a person instead of addressing the argument or issue. (§5.2)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch5-appeal-to-authority">
        <title>Appeal to illegitimate authority</title>
        <p>A fallacy that relies on a source that is not an appropriate authority for the claim at issue, or that misuses authority in place of evidence. (§5.2)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch5-appeal-to-emotion">
        <title>Appeal to emotion</title>
        <p>A fallacy that substitutes emotional pressure for relevant support. (§5.2)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch5-appeal-to-popularity">
        <title>Appeal to popularity</title>
        <p>A fallacy that treats a claim as true or reasonable merely because many people believe or favor it. (§5.2)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch5-begging-the-question">
        <title>Begging the question</title>
        <p>A fallacy in which the argument assumes what it is supposed to prove. (§5.4)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch5-complex-question">
        <title>Complex question</title>
        <p>A fallacy in which a question presupposes something controversial or unsupported. (§5.4)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch5-equivocation">
        <title>Equivocation</title>
        <p>A fallacy in which a key term shifts meaning across an argument. (§5.2)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch5-fallacy">
        <title>Fallacy</title>
        <p>A recurring pattern of bad reasoning. (§5.1)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch5-false-cause">
        <title>False cause</title>
        <p>A fallacy that infers a causal connection without adequate causal evidence. (§5.3)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch5-false-dichotomy">
        <title>False dichotomy</title>
        <p>A fallacy that presents too few options as if they exhausted the possibilities. (§5.4)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch5-hasty-generalization">
        <title>Hasty generalization</title>
        <p>A fallacy that draws a broad conclusion from too little or unrepresentative evidence. (§5.3)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch5-red-herring">
        <title>Red herring</title>
        <p>A fallacy that diverts attention to an issue that is not relevant to the conclusion under discussion. (§5.2)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch5-rigid-application">
        <title>Rigid application of a generalization</title>
        <p>A fallacy that applies a general rule too mechanically, ignoring relevant exceptions or context. (§5.3)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch5-slippery-slope">
        <title>Slippery slope</title>
        <p>A fallacy that moves from a first step to an extreme outcome without adequate support for the chain of consequences. (§5.3)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch5-straw-person">
        <title>Straw person</title>
        <p>A fallacy that attacks a distorted or weakened version of an opponent's position. (§5.2)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch5-suppressed-evidence">
        <title>Suppressed evidence</title>
        <p>A fallacy that leaves out important information that would weaken or change the argument. (§5.4)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch5-weak-analogy">
        <title>Weak analogy</title>
        <p>A fallacy that relies on a comparison whose relevant similarities are too weak to support the conclusion. (§5.3)</p>
      </li>
    </dl>

  </section>

  <exercises xml:id="exercises-ch5">
    <title>End-of-Chapter Exercises</title>

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch5-s01">
      <title>Exercise Set 1: Identifying Fallacies of Relevance</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          For each passage, identify the fallacy of relevance being
          committed and explain briefly why the argument fails.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch5-s01-01">
        <statement>
          <p>You can't take Senator Carter's argument about climate policy seriously. She drives a gas-powered SUV.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch5-s01-02">
        <statement>
          <p>Most Americans say they want lower taxes. So lowering taxes is the right policy.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch5-s01-03">
        <statement>
          <p>If we don't act now, your children will grow up in a country we no longer recognize. So we have to pass this bill.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch5-s01-04">
        <statement>
          <p>The opposition wants stronger background checks for firearm purchases. They want to disarm law-abiding Americans. We should reject their proposal.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch5-s01-05">
        <statement>
          <p>Reporter: Senator, your office's records show you accepted a donation that may have violated state ethics rules. Senator: Look, the real story here is the way the previous administration left this state in a fiscal crisis.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch5-s01-06">
        <statement>
          <p>Freedom is the most American of values. The Constitution protects freedom. So criminalizing the public release of any information must be unconstitutional.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch5-s02">
      <title>Exercise Set 2: Identifying Fallacies of Weak Inductive Support</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          For each passage, identify the fallacy of weak inductive
          support and explain why the inductive support is weaker
          than the argument suggests.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch5-s02-01">
        <statement>
          <p>I know two people who got laid off from data center construction projects last month. Clearly the data center industry is collapsing.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch5-s02-02">
        <statement>
          <p>Inflation rose for three months after the new tariffs went into effect. The tariffs are causing the inflation.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch5-s02-03">
        <statement>
          <p>If we allow background checks for firearm sales, the next step will be a registry, then licensing requirements, then confiscation. We have to oppose any background check legislation.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch5-s02-04">
        <statement>
          <p>The current administration's expansion of executive power is just like what happened in pre-war Germany. We are headed for the same outcome.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch5-s02-05">
        <statement>
          <p>Most members of Congress vote in line with what their constituents say they want. So when critics point to a specific vote that ran against constituent polling, they must be cherry-picking outliers that don't really matter.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch5-s03">
      <title>Exercise Set 3: Identifying Fallacies of Presumption</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          For each passage, identify the fallacy of presumption and
          explain what is being presumed without argument.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch5-s03-01">
        <statement>
          <p>Either we secure our borders or we accept lawlessness. We must secure our borders.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch5-s03-02">
        <statement>
          <p>Why does the governor continue to ignore the state's struggling rural counties?</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch5-s03-03">
        <statement>
          <p>The party of working people supports working people. So working people should support the party.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch5-s03-04">
        <statement>
          <p>Our state's manufacturing employment grew by 4,000 jobs last year. The new business tax credit was clearly a success.</p>
          <p>(Hint: what other evidence about the state's economy might bear on whether the tax credit was a success?)</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch5-s04">
      <title>Exercise Set 4: Mixed Identification</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          For each passage, identify the fallacy committed (it
          could be from any of the three groups) and explain
          briefly. Some passages may commit more than one fallacy.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch5-s04-01">
        <statement>
          <p>Free speech is a constitutional right. Banning a speaker from a private platform is an attack on free speech. So banning a speaker from a private platform is unconstitutional.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch5-s04-02">
        <statement>
          <p>Of course Senator Hayes supports the data center expansion. Her largest donors include data center developers.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch5-s04-03">
        <statement>
          <p>The administration says the Iran strikes were necessary. The administration includes generals and security experts. So the strikes were necessary.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch5-s04-04">
        <statement>
          <p>You're either with the troops or you're against them. Anyone who criticizes the operation is against the troops.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch5-s04-05">
        <statement>
          <p>The bill's opponents say it would hurt small businesses. But the bill's supporters include people who have run small businesses. So the bill won't hurt small businesses.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch5-s05">
      <title>Exercise Set 5: Legitimate or Fallacious?</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Each of the following passages has the surface appearance
          of a fallacy from this chapter. For each, decide whether
          the argument actually commits the fallacy, or whether it
          is the legitimate cousin. Justify briefly.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch5-s05-01">
        <statement>
          <p>According to the Centers for Disease Control's most recent report, vaccination rates among five-year-olds in this state have fallen below the threshold required for measles herd immunity. We should expect more outbreaks.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch5-s05-02">
        <statement>
          <p>The bridge's design uses the same load-distribution geometry as the bridge that failed in Minneapolis in 2007. We should treat this design as suspect until the engineering review is complete.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch5-s05-03">
        <statement>
          <p>Senator Lewis voted for the bill. Her brother-in-law owns a company that stands to benefit from it. The senator should have recused herself.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch5-s05-04">
        <statement>
          <p>If we pass this surveillance authorization, the same infrastructure will exist for any future administration to use. We should be cautious about expanding it.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch5-s06">
      <title>Exercise Set 6: Construct Your Own</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          For each fallacy below, write a short example argument
          that commits it. Use a contemporary political topic of
          your choice. Then write a one-sentence diagnosis
          explaining what the fallacy is doing in your example.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch5-s06-01">
        <statement>
          <p>Straw person.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch5-s06-02">
        <statement>
          <p>False dichotomy.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch5-s06-03">
        <statement>
          <p>Slippery slope.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch5-s06-04">
        <statement>
          <p>Equivocation.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

  </exercises>

</chapter>
